You are here when a feature has a **visual surface** and the main decision is how it looks: a new UI screen, landing page, component, visual redesign. For visual work a mockup is not an illustration but the **carrier of design decisions**: the accepted mockup is the design gate, after which the rest is usually mechanical.

Not for server/non-visual tasks — there the decisions are textual and no mockup is needed.

## Method: show, don't describe (by any available means)

The medium is **any visual preview available to the current agent**: artifacts, a self-contained HTML preview in a browser, rendered images, etc. The medium is secondary — the principle matters: the user **sees** the design, does not read a description of it. What to reproduce regardless of medium:

- **Variants side by side** — 2–4 layouts next to each other (interactive medium — toggles for **variant** / **theme** light-dark / **width** narrow-wide-full in one mockup; static medium — separate renders), to compare live.
- **Pixel-precise** — iterate on concrete edits ("smaller gap", "chip further left"), not on vague words.
- **Full-width adaptive** — no artificial `max-width` constraint if the product is full-width.

## Iteration discipline

- **After 2 consecutive "not quite"** — don't run a third blind iteration. Bring in the ui-ux skill + show variants **side by side** (variant/theme/width toggles), let the user point pixel-precisely.
- **Don't bail to "known limitation / won't fix"** before explicitly listing the remaining options. "So it can't be done?" from the user = a signal you bailed early.
- **A failed CSS experiment — revert it immediately**, don't hoard it as "defense in depth".

## Output: the accepted mockup is the design gate

The accepted mockup carries the design decisions — the spec text after it can be thin (see the spec step of `sdh-phase-workflow`). And this is usually where all the judgment is settled and the rest is mechanical → the cycle's **autonomous mode** naturally kicks in (see `sdh-release-lifecycle`): the user grants a carry-forward OK at mockup acceptance, and Implementation → Test → the documentation part of Closure roll on without per-stage approvals.
